          </p>

          <h3 class="space-font">Graphics Card (GPU) - The Gaming Heart</h3>

          <p>
            The graphics card is the most important component for gaming performance. It renders all
            the visuals you see on screen. In 2025, the main choices are:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>NVIDIA GeForce RTX 40 Series:</strong> Excellent performance, ray tracing, DLSS
              upscaling. The RTX 4070 offers great 1440p performance around £500.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>AMD Radeon RX 7000 Series:</strong> Strong price-to-performance, good at higher
              resolutions. The RX 7800 XT is excellent value at similar prices.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intel Arc:</strong> Budget-friendly options, though driver support still maturing.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="highlight-box">
            <p style="margin: 0;">
              <strong>Budget Tip:</strong> Allocate 30-40% of your total build budget to the graphics
              card. It's the component that most directly affects gaming performance, and skimping here
              will limit your entire system.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h3 class="space-font">Processor (CPU) - The Brain</h3>

          <p>
            The CPU handles game logic, physics, AI, and coordinates all other components. For
            gaming in 2026:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>AMD Ryzen 5 7600:</strong> Excellent value for gaming, 6 cores/12 threads, around
              £200
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>AMD Ryzen 7 7800X3D:</strong> Currently the best gaming CPU, amazing for competitive
              games, around £350
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intel Core i5-14600K:</strong> Great all-rounder for gaming and productivity, around
              £280
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intel Core i7-14700K:</strong> High-end option with excellent multi-tasking, around
              £380
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">Memory (RAM) - Short-Term Memory</h3>

          <p>RAM stores data your computer needs to access quickly. For gaming:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>16GB DDR5:</strong> Minimum recommended for modern gaming</li>
            <li>
              <strong>32GB DDR5:</strong> Ideal if you stream, multitask, or want future-proofing
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Speed matters:</strong> Look for DDR5-5600 or faster, with low latency (CL30 or
              better)
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">Storage - Where Games Live</h3>

          <p>Modern games are huge (100GB+ each), so storage choices matter:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>NVMe SSD (Primary):</strong> At least 1TB for Windows and frequently played games.
              Fast loading times make a real difference.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Additional Storage:</strong> Consider a 2TB+ secondary drive for game libraries.
              Even a SATA SSD works well for this.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Avoid HDDs for games:</strong> Traditional hard drives cause painfully long load
              times in modern games.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">Motherboard - The Foundation</h3>

          <p>The motherboard connects all components. Choose based on your CPU:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>AMD AM5 Platform:</strong> B650 boards offer great value; X670 for enthusiast features
            </li>
            <li><strong>Intel LGA 1700:</strong> B760 for budget builds; Z790 for overclocking</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Key features to look for:</strong> Adequate USB ports, M.2 slots for SSDs, good
              VRM cooling
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">Power Supply (PSU) - Clean Power</h3>

          <p>
            Never cheap out on the power supply - a poor one can damage components or cause
            instability:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Wattage:</strong> 650W for mid-range builds, 750W-850W for high-end</li>
            <li><strong>Efficiency:</strong> Look for 80+ Gold certification minimum</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Brands:</strong> Stick to reputable brands - Corsair, EVGA, Seasonic, be quiet!
            </li>
          </ul>

