            better temperatures and quieter operation:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Tower air coolers:</strong> Excellent value, reliable, quiet. Noctua NH-D15 or be
              quiet! Dark Rock Pro 4
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>AIO liquid coolers:</strong> Better for high-end CPUs, cleaner look. 240mm minimum,
              360mm for enthusiast builds
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 class="space-font" id="mistakes">Common Gaming PC Build Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

          <p>
            Even experienced builders make mistakes. Here are the most common pitfalls and how to
            avoid them:
          </p>

          <h3 class="space-font">1. Unbalanced Builds</h3>

          <p>
            Spending too much on one component while neglecting others creates bottlenecks. A £700
            GPU paired with a £80 CPU will underperform. Keep your build balanced according to your
            budget tier.
          </p>

          <h3 class="space-font">2. Forgetting About Total Cost</h3>

          <p>Your budget needs to cover everything - not just the main components. Don't forget:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>Windows licence (or use Windows unactivated initially)</li>
            <li>Monitor (a great PC deserves a good display)</li>
            <li>Keyboard and mouse</li>
            <li>Additional case fans if needed</li>
            <li>Thermal paste (usually included with coolers)</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">3. Incompatible Components</h3>

          <p>Before purchasing, verify compatibility:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>CPU + Motherboard:</strong> Must use the same socket (AM5 for Ryzen 7000, LGA 1700
              for Intel 12th-14th gen)
            </li>
            <li><strong>RAM + Motherboard:</strong> Check DDR4 vs DDR5 support</li>
            <li><strong>GPU + Case:</strong> Verify GPU length clearance</li>
            <li><strong>Cooler + Case:</strong> Check cooler height clearance</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="highlight-box">
            <p style="margin: 0;">
              <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Use PCPartPicker (pcpartpicker.com) to plan your build. It automatically
              checks compatibility and compares prices across UK retailers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h3 class="space-font">4. Inadequate Cooling</h3>

          <p>
            Hot components throttle performance and reduce lifespan. Ensure good case airflow with
            intake fans at the front and exhaust at the back/top. Modern GPUs generate significant
            heat - airflow-focused cases with mesh fronts are recommended.
          </p>

          <h3 class="space-font">5. Rushing the Build</h3>

          <p>
            Take your time during assembly. Read the motherboard manual. Double-check connections. A
            rushed build often leads to troubleshooting headaches later - or worse, damaged
            components.
          </p>

          <h2 class="space-font" id="build-vs-buy">Build vs Buy: What's Right for You?</h2>

          <p>There are three main options for getting a gaming PC:</p>

          <h3 class="space-font">Build It Yourself</h3>

          <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Save 10-20% compared to pre-built</li>
            <li>Choose exactly the components you want</li>
            <li>Learn skills for future maintenance and upgrades</li>
            <li>Satisfying achievement</li>
          </ul>

          <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Time investment (research + building)</li>
            <li>Risk of mistakes if inexperienced</li>
            <li>Troubleshooting issues alone</li>
            <li>Separate warranties for each component</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="space-font">Buy Pre-Built</h3>

          <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Plug and play convenience</li>
            <li>Single warranty for the whole system</li>
            <li>Technical support included</li>
          </ul>

          <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Premium pricing (often 15-25% more)</li>
            <li>Limited customisation</li>
            <li>Sometimes use cheaper components (PSUs, motherboards)</li>
          </ul>

